Comment: After playing this person and losing to my own blunder, I was not going to let that happen in this game. He opened with b4 and I figured he was going Bb2 next.
I'm playing Black and open with e5
He pushes his pawn to b5 and I ask if he is trying to promote his b pawn?
I am able to develop my DSB to c5.
This opens his LSB  to look down diagonal protecting his hanging pawn on b5.  and his Queen to look down the other diagonal.
I develop my Knight with plans to get my King to safety
He brings out his wing pawn which does not control the center.
I take advantage of the open center and now my LSB has a view of the h3 diagonal.
He decides to defend the center threatening my DSB.
Pawn takes pawn, this doubles my pawns on the d-file for now.
He takes back my pawn again attacking my DSB.
I drop by DSB back and am now looking at his d2 pawn.
He decides to develop his LSB in front of his King, this leave just his knight on his King-side to be develop.
I decide to Castle Kingside to get my King to safety.
He develops Nf3 which completes King-side development.
I want to develop my Knight on my Queen-side but his b5 pawn has been in the way so I simply play a6 to see what he decides to do about my attacking pawn.
He ignores my attack of his b5 pawn and instead castles King-side.
I take his b-pawn and also open up my Rook to get in the game.
Bishop takes and again my knight can not develop to c6.
This move is normally saved until I develop my minor pieces, but e4 was open and I wanted my Knight there now. There were no attackers and I had my d pawn watching my back.
